segments.text: I don't like the intro.
Okay, we were talking about the philosophy of examining boards and protection of the public and the
Federal Trade Commission practice rules and so forth.
What's your general attitude toward the philosophy of whether or not examining boards really are in the best interest of the public?
I feel that the duty and responsibility of the board
is to protect the public.
That's basically the main reason that the board exists is not for any other reason except to protect the public.
And in examining these applicants,
It's difficult to visualize, so to speak, but I think it's the responsibility of the board to not figure out necessarily who is the most capable individual
taking examination, but how far can we go with an individual and let him have a license and he won't be a danger to the public?
See what I'm talking about?
Instead of eliminating them or figuring out which one is the best, we try to figure out
How sorry can a man be and still not be a danger to the public?
It creates a problem.
I saw an editorial in the American Animal Hospital Journal the other day.
It was...
I don't know whether it was an editorial or a letter to the editor.
Of course, there is some difference between those two.
But the statement made in the journal was...

that he looked in the not too far distant future for the only thing for an examining board to do, if they had a diploma from a legitimate veterinary school, that they were obligated to let him practice anywhere, anytime.
Do you think that time may be coming?
I would hope not.
I think that there should be some changes.
I feel that we should examine on a regional basis rather than just a state.
Possibly Arkansas, Louisiana, Texas, Oklahoma, and even New Mexico could band together and have an examination.
And if I pass that examination, I can practice in any of those states.
It probably never will come.
I have some ideas about education, too.
I don't know why I bring it up at this time, but
I firmly believe that our educational process would be better utilized if we had an interchange
of students from these various veterinary schools.
Three or four students from Texas could go to Iowa, and three or four from Iowa could go to Washington, and three or four from Washington go to Cornell, intermingle them.
Then those kids would come back home
You know, every institution is strong in different areas.
And they could bring information back from Iowa that would be beneficial to the state of Texas.
And we could take information from Texas or background material from Texas and it would be beneficial to these other schools.
And why they don't do it, I don't know.
But back to this matter of examination, I think that this matter of a degree, of a diploma from a school, doesn't...

qualify you to practice, say, in Texas because you may have a background, a moral background that's not suitable, a type of person that we wouldn't want to practice in Texas, even though you had a fine record from the school that you come from.
That would be the...
The main reason that I would see to not just accept them on a diploma.
We have had graduates from A&M College that really, and I'm sure other schools have too, that they'd rather they hadn't graduated, but they thought, well, the board will catch them.
We'll let them get on through school, but the board will cut them off.
They should have been cut off right down there before they got their diploma.
Maybe we shouldn't say anything about that.
That's all right.
Well, it's happened.
It's happened.
And I'm sure it's happened in other places, too.
In the growth of the Texas Veteran Medical Association, it's, of course, grown with the number of practitioners.

Do you feel that there, to begin with, our practice acts didn't have very much to say about the practice, but in the last several years the practice act, especially during the 50s, became quite stringent, and 60s also.
Do you feel that the TVMA really did
An excellent service in getting those things worked out together with the legislators.
Specifically, what would you have represented?
Well, the greatest change in the Practice Act, I believe, took place in the 50s.
Up until that time, there hadn't been much change in it since it was originally inaugurated in about 1911.
At that time, the Practice Act, Paul Blunt was instrumental in working with that at that time.
Do you feel the TVMA did the public a great service in working that out?
I don't recall specifics right at this time.
But no doubt it was an attempt to kind of bring us to modernize the practice act, shall we say.
And it probably has deficiencies and things that we wouldn't prefer.
But any time you go before the legislature
a practice act, there's no telling what you'll end up with.
But I think that generally, by and large, they've done a pretty good job on that.
I think you'll agree that practice has changed a lot since you first went into the profession in 1939 until the present day.
You've already stated that practice was difficult back in those days due to lack of equipment and medications and so forth.
Tell us about some of the specific things and specific areas that you've seen changes during your career in the practice of medicine.
There are just many things that have come about, instruments, drugs, procedures, that have made practice more enjoyable.
I pointed out here one thing in particular that
was available that wasn't available when I started in practice.
It was shortly after the war.
That was the introduction of sulfapyridine, which we used to treat foot rot in cattle.
I recall once I went out on a call northwest of town shortly after sulfapyridine was available.
Up until that time, we'd have to put bandages and use this old pow blue and whatnot on these cases and change the bandage and all for these foot rot cases, you know.
after self-pyridine was available, you take two ounces of that and put it in a pint of water and give it intravenously to the animal and turn him loose.
Not ever bandage him.
And this old lady wasn't going to pay me because she came out to treat that cow and didn't even put a bandage on her foot.
I said, well, the cow got all right, didn't it?
Yeah, but you didn't do like you should have.
You didn't bandage it.
But, I mean, that's just one example.
And here...
That's one of those things you went up against in practice.
That's right.
You get it fixed better and they don't think you've worked hard enough.
That's right.
They haven't worked hard enough.
Another thing that's come about in these modern years is the discovery of what causes wheat pasture poisoning.
That used to be a big problem to us.
Those old cows, you'd push them around and they'd become paralyzed and fight you and all that.
And of course, it's magnesium deficiency.
We've...
In 39, and even when I started into practice in Fort Worth, we had the so-called X disease problem, chlorinated naphthalene poisoning.

We didn't know what it was, and Dr. Smith had come up to see me, and we'd have anywhere from one to two to several in a herd involved, and he'd take cultures, and he'd look, and he'd do this, that, and the other, and then...
About 1951 or 1952, we had an outbreak of X disease, and catalept was traced to cottonseed cake.
They had...
They had sucked all the normal oils out of that cake and then used mineral oil, incorporated mineral oil into that meal so that it would cake, see?
So they could make a cake.
And this particular mineral oil had chlorinated naphthalene in it, which is a product that's used to make oils stronger and more durable in machinery, see?
But it doesn't work very good in cattle.
But that was a big problem and a big headache to us.
And when that was finally found out, I remember Dr. Smith was up here one day talking to us after we'd found out what caused the X disease and all.
And he was talking to the head of the Trader's Oil mill out here.
He was in the crowd.
And he said, we...
had worked for years trying to figure out what caused this X disease.
And then this Trader's oil mill provides us with this wonderful experiment.
It was millions of dollars that cost Trader's.
But we found that out.
And we stopped the recurrence of X disease by removing that.
There used to be in old tractor oils and greases.
And those cattle would get out and lick on it.
And you've probably seen it in your practice.
Another thing that we know about now is oak bud poisoning and acorn poisoning in horses.
And we see more nitrate poisoning and we have better ways of handling it.
Because of improved fertilizers, it brought on more nitrate poisoning.
We used to see these photosensitization problems that we didn't know what caused them.
We'd see a white-footed horse that would get an eczema and an irritation on his feet.
And now we know that it's part of that photosensitization complex.
The treatment of coccidiosis of all animals, before we had sulfa drugs, we were just fighting in the dark.
Along with other drugs that we have, we have others now, but your sulfa was one of the first drugs that was effective against coccidiosis.
bacterial pneumonias back before the war, that was a big problem, but with the advent of sulfurs and penicillin, well, your bacterial pneumonias became a lesser problem.
We still have a ways to go with
treatment of viral resp in fact all viral diseases now in vaccines we have rhino pneumonitis vaccine for horses your influenza vaccine which along with your strep bactrims almost
has eliminated the old distemper problem in horses if immunization is properly carried out.
And think of the improvements that have come about in vaccines, viral vaccines for dogs and cats, just since the war.
Would you write Danny?
The coronavirus vaccines have come into being for these diarrhea problems in caves.
We now have infectious bovine rhinotracheitis vaccine, bovine virus diarrhea vaccine, which we knew nothing about back when I started practicing.
We've gone through the
the lepto complex.
And we now know the different strains or whatnot of lepto.
And we have Bactrins that are effective against those particular strains.
We have Vibrio vaccine, which we didn't have back then.
We have improved rabies vaccines.
In the last 40 years, we've seen the diagnosis and control of swine ear syphilis become more effective.
I remember about 1950,
I had suspected that I had erysipelas and some swine out here.
And the old federal veterinarian in charge said, well, there's only been, now this was as late as 1950, there's only been one outbreak of erysipelas reported in Texas.
That was down in, oh, way down around the King Ranch.
Down around Kingsville.
And I said, well, I believe I have some.
He said, bring me an enlarged hock, you know, those joints, enlarged joints.
He said, bring me a joint, an enlarged joint, and I'll send it up to Maryland, Beltsville.
That's where they, before they had the disease laboratory out of date.
They'll send it up to Beltsville.
So I packed it in Borax or something like that, you know, and
We shipped it up there, and about two months later, they reported back, yeah, you've got ear syphilis.
Two months later?
Yeah, yeah, at least two months.
But your syphilis organism grows very slowly.
Yes, right.
That's true, that's true.
But it took that long.
It wouldn't take that long with these newer, sophisticated procedures.
But what did I have?
I had only ear syphilis serum.
I would give these baby pigs this serum.
Then we'd turn them out on that infected ground, and they'd do all right.
I'd turn a litter out there without it, and man, they'd just wither up.
They'd just dry up.
You know what I mean.
We've eradicated hog collar in my lifetime in practice.
We've made wonderful strides in controlling anaplasmosis.
A little aerosol or some of the arsenicals of prayer was about all we had back in 1939 and 40 and 41 for anaplasmosis.
And now...
We have vaccines to protect the animal and antibiotics to control the carrier phase of the disease.
And it's much easier to handle.
And we have the tools to take care of it today where we didn't back in the day.
We've made tremendous progress in the field of nutrition.
Our research has carried us into the field of immunology, and we can pinpoint these immunodeficiencies now that we had no idea what was going on 40 years ago.
Laminitis in horses, treatment is still a problem, but...
The modern day x-rays and research gives us some tools to kind of predict.
We know that we can produce laminitis by, researchers have done that by, you know, just by feeding high carbohydrate diet.
And they can tell pretty well when the animal is going to come down with laminitis.
And through our x-rays, we can give a pretty good prognosis on how the animal is going to come along and whether you've got a rotation there or not.
And we're much further along than we were 40 or 50 years ago in the field of laminitis.
Bacterial diarrhea in the young, we have much better prevention and control of that.
Our Clostridium infections, and especially cattle,
They were a real problem originally in the unvaccinated individuals.

And even in the vaccinated ones, we had some of those, then you had and some of those others that were still there that we weren't able to, until they got these new, more sophisticated methods of diagnosis, we couldn't

couldn't diagnose it but they've incorporated all those things into their into the vaccines now and uh we don't look back we just give them the whole wagon load and it and and it pretty well prevents it we've got anti-inflammatory we've got butazolidine banamine and all those things that we did we didn't have those didn't have anything just just an old aspirin was the closest thing we had to it back there then
We've had tremendous progress in the field of urinary stimulants, Lasix, Hydrazide, and those things for edema and urinary stimulants.
But the old Pastorella bug is still with us.
You know, they used to diagnose hemorrhagic septicemia, which was your old Pastorella.
And we went through a phase there.
before the war where we thought it was in the picture on pathology, and then they phased it out and said, no, now it's come back.
It's involved in a lot of these shipping fever deals where you have the viruses and then the pastoral moves in.
But it's been interesting to see that.
Now, we still have problems with the viruses, but we can pretty well...
control the straight pasteurilosis by bacteria and antibiotics, of course.
Herd health is much better.
We know more about advising people on herd health today than we did years ago.
Internal parasites.
We were just, phenothiazine was just on the horizon in 1940.
We were just beginning to use a little of it.
Before that, there really wasn't much of anything, was there?
Just tobacco dust.
Oil of kinapodium and tobacco dust.
Oil of kinapodium and tobacco dust and nicotine sulfate and that kind of stuff, you know.
Which was no doubt better than nothing.
But there again, you had to talk about pasture rotation and that sort of thing.
That's right.
That's true.
Antimidics just weren't there.
Right.
We've seen old smear 62, which is diphenylamine, you know, and black.
It had to come along to...
treat for screwworms, but now we've eradicated screwworms.
Now, the modern veterinarian, the young veterinarian, my son knows not a damn thing about screwworms, but wasn't that a great day when we got rid of screwworms?
Let me ask you a question.
You know, you've done the same thing.
You go out and treat a cow surgically or treat one with screwworms, and you'd have to use Smear 62.
And the smear was a good word for it because you've got to smear it all over everywhere, including under your fingernails.
Now, why did it take so long to figure out that you didn't have to use lamp black to dilute your diphenylamine with or anything else?
You know, almost anything will kill screw arms.
You just need a vehicle to take it in or even oil solutions.
Why in the world did Smear 62 have to ever be invented in the first place?
It goes back to the old pine tar.
They had to have something that looked like pine tar.
You know, we used to use pine tar around them to kind of prevent re-infestation of screw worms.
And I guess they had to kind of duplicate something of a pine tar nature.
Lord, no.
But there are a lot of vehicles that can take that stuff in besides lamp black.
That's right.
But they were looking for something comparable to what they'd always had.
They weren't improving on the past.
They were just duplicating it.
Well, zinc oxide, you know, sticks real good.
Yeah.
Put it in that.
That's right.
Different color.
Oh, that's right.
Very true.
Very true.
For us white folks.
But the day they got rid of that glaring black stuff is a great day, too.
Well, that's right.
Back there in those days, I'm talking about before the war, we knew nothing about chlordane, BHC, DDT, organophosphates.
All of those things came on later, you know.
All we had back there then was arsenical dip, crisodip, and the old lacrycursalis saponatus, which is the BAI, the old BAI.
And tick tocks.
Tick tocks.
Remember tick tocks?
Well, that's what we used on ticks.
It didn't kill the ticks, but it sure made the dogs irritated.
Oh, yeah.
What was the basis for that?
Oh, they had some irritating material in there.
They felt if it irritated enough, if they didn't come back with...
Swell testicles that came back with sore eyes.
Yeah, yeah, right.
I remember the name, but I didn't associate the product.
We've had cortisones and antihistamines are new, and the adenoviruses weren't heard of back there then.
Blue tongue in sheep was recognized in this country in 1938.
A vaccine for...
The vaccine for contagious exanthema of sheep had just been developed down at the experiment station.
I was told when I was a senior that TB had been eradicated, and the BAI said brucellosis would be eradicated in three or four years.
That was in 38.
We knew nothing of chlamydial, mycotic, or mycotoxins.
And all of those things were to come after that.
That's just a few of the many things that occurred to me this morning.
And that doesn't scratch the surface.
Yes.
Dan, I'd like to ask you another kind of personal question.
You know, back in the good old days,
when we had all these difficulties and problems and so forth and so on, the clients didn't expect quite as much of you as they expect of you now, did they?
Well, they compared you to that quack, see?
You had to try to do a better job and sell them.
And let them convince them that you could do a better job than that quack could do.
Today, with all of these television programs and all of these stories about, I saw they had a, somewhere the other day they had a horse with a, somebody had put a false leg on him.
so he could make a breeder.
And they think every horse that breaks his leg now that you can put a false leg on him and keep him going.
I guess we've brought that on ourselves, though, you know.
The doctors have been smart enough to say, well, now look here, we're not sure about this.
We're going to have to send some of this into the laboratory.
We're going to have to do this and that and the other bit.
We thought we had to give a diagnosis right across the table, you know, and we were caused by a whole lot of that.
I can't help but recall somewhere about 15 years ago, I think it was about 15 years ago, perhaps a little less, Jacques Genny operated on a
on a horse's fetlock that had been injured in a race for a comminuted bone situation in there.
Did a beautiful job of surgery, put it together, and the dog and the patient mutilated itself heavily on recovery from anesthesia.
And the horse was subsequently euthanized and got a tremendous amount of
national publicity as you're aware.

Dr. Wagenstein, who was an old, at that time he was quite old, of course he's now deceased, but he's a surgeon, a human surgeon from the University of Minnesota Medical Schools, invented the Wagenstein pump and so forth and so on.
And he says they certainly must be able to do better than that and come up with a better way.
Of all the challenges that you have met in veterinary medicine and in equine practice, do you think there is a greater one than the sedation and anesthesia of horses for long, drawn-out surgeries?
I'm talking about, you know, fracture repairs that take two or three hours and so forth and so on.
They have come a long ways in that field in the last few years.
You know, anything I couldn't do with mag chloral, I just didn't do it.
But with this guacolate and with the respiratory thing, they've improved that procedure materially.
I believe in this particular horse, didn't they use inhalation anesthesia?
That was on that mare, that good mare that died, wasn't it?
Yes, while it was in the race, you know.
Yeah, that's that good mare that was going to win everything.
Yes.
And I think Bill Reed was in on that, too.
Bill Reed was in on it.
Uh...
Yeah, I believe they did use inhalation on that.
That's just about the best you can use, so to speak.
Right, right.
There are still some of those that are a real challenge, right?
Oh, that's very true.
That's very true.
There's a tremendous amount of research going on in that field right now.
See, you don't need to give up yet.
You can probably figure out something to help that out yet.
Well, I'll leave that to the younger people.
By the way, there's a thing that we're doing to our students that is wrong.
But in a way, I guess we all thought it until we got out and found out differently.
They teach these kids that they're worth maybe $30,000 or $40,000 a year when they get out.
And these kids are looking to get rich quick.
They're going to retire after about five years.
In practice, well, you don't do it that way.
You don't do it that way.
You know what I'm talking about.
I know what you're talking about.
You had some other investments besides practice.
Your outside investments allowed you to retire.
If I had to have depended just on my practice, my wife and kids and I could have eaten pretty good.
But we'd have never been able to retire and go to Europe every once in a while or take a trip when we get ready.
It's your outside investments that takes care of you or keeps you in the poorhouse, I think, most of the time.
I was going to ask you that question, and you've pretty well brought it up.
The next question is about the youngsters.
They don't seem to have the camaraderie or the desire to get together and solve their problems mutually.
They feel, to me, they seem that the problems have been solved.
Now they need to
ride off into the sunset and do their own thing and that there isn't any real need for the camaraderie, especially in local associations.
They can see where a state association can do things, you know, on a higher level with their seminars and so on.
But there's no need for the local people to get together to discuss their problem cases or how can we serve the public better.
Do you seem to have any
Feeling toward that or observation also or not?
Hadn't changed a darn bit in 50 years.
But do you feel the youngsters have the camaraderie that we used to?
I feel that there's always been a
a little petty jealousy or something that prevents them from sitting down and discussing the problems and working them out as a group.
I remember, let me see.
Yeah, it was right after the war.
46, 47, somewhere along there.
I was going to get our local association all involved.
I was going to get everybody in.
Somebody said, well, Dr. McQuistion, he never comes to the meeting.
I said, I'll get him.
I called him.
I said, say, we've got a veterinary meeting tonight.
I'll come by and pick you up.
And we'd go, oh, no, Dan.
He said.

I won't go he says they'll get down there and argue about what they're going to charge for rabies vaccination and then they'll all go home and do differently tomorrow there there's just I don't know there's something
I wish I knew the answer to that question you posed.
I'd like to see local veterinary groups be more better organized and more cooperative and just get along better.
But really they never have in this area.
That's not good, but do you have any suggestions?
No, I don't.
What I know is that down in our local association, we had fellows like Elmo Crenshaw and Vernon Dietz and Jack Gray.
They were unusual individuals.
And we all hung together like just a bunch of peas in a pod, and whenever things weren't going right or we had a
problem or we didn't think we were doing client right.
We'd all get together and see what was wrong and try to straighten the thing out.
That's the way it ought to be.
But the new group, they'll come if you're going to have a special technique, new technique on fracture fixation or something like that.
They'll get them out, but if it's just to talk over
how we can better serve the community and so forth.
Okay, I'm ready.
Prior to that stuff.

But there are two things that I kind of missed on the way coming up and I've done several dozen oral interviews and I always feel bad when I finish that there are a certain number of things we didn't go over.
One of them is we didn't discuss your

your family, your brothers and sisters, and then we didn't discuss your marriage and your family, and I think it would be well to mention your brothers and sisters and what they did and do, and also your marriage and your family and what they did and do.
Yes.
Well, I think that
take my family first, not this family, but my brothers and sisters.
I was very fortunate to be a member of a family such as I had.
Not an ounce of jealousy nor greed in any one of them.
Who were your brothers and sisters?
Well, W.L.
William Anderson.
Who was named after your father, right?
Named after my father, and he's a veterinarian in Dallas.
And incidentally, in 120 years of...
existence of the American Veterinary Medical Association.
I believe it's, well, it's longer than that now, 125 years ago.
There's only been two brothers served as president of AVMA, and that was Dub and myself.
And I'm very proud of him because he has been a very outstanding and successful veterinarian, and I'm, as I say, I'm
Real, real proud of the job that he's done.
I had two sisters, a younger sister, Mary Jean, who is married to Horace Lee Williams, and they live in Rockwall, and he has been very successful.
He's retired now.
He's been successful as a developer, and he had a lumber business and a...
concrete, ready-mix concrete outfit.
I had an older sister, Virginia, who passed away last Christmas Eve.
She has two children.
One lives in Rockwall, is Mary Sue.
She's married to Bob Smith, who is
Oh, Executive Vice President of the Federal Reserve in Dallas, or some position similar to that.
Mike, her brother, is Assistant Superintendent.
He's just been elected to position in a high school over in Arlington.
My wife, Frances, Frances Smith,

Frances grew up in Garland, which is only 10 miles from Rockwell, but, uh, she was a year or two younger than I, and I never did know her until, uh, oh, I was in the Army, I think, before I ever met her.
I tried to meet her old off to Crenshaw as an old veterinarian over at Garland, and, and, uh,

He tried to introduce me to her several times when I was down there at Tara, but she saw old Dr. Crenshaw, the way he operated, and she didn't want to have anything to do with the darn brother, Marion.
But I finally met her one night.
My cousin introduced me to her.
Oh, she finally got that out of her system.
Yeah, finally introduced me.
Well, the thing of it was, it was during the war, and all the good men had gone off to war, and she thought I was the last chance, see?
But you know, I was pretty lucky.
She has stayed at home and reared two fine sons while I ran around all over the country and tried to make a living.
And my older son, Danny, has a degree in business from Texas Western University.
He's been in a number of positions around the country in sales work.
He was up in Montana and about a year ago, when I gave up my practice, I was ordering stuff, I was paying invoices, I was the delivery boy for everything I needed.
And I was just handyman around there.
And I said, by gosh, I've got a harder job.
I'm working harder now than I did when I was practicing.
So we brought him back here to take over that job as...
